# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: magnetic-materials
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] Generally, antiferromagnetic order may exist at sufficiently low temperatures, but vanishes at and above the Néel temperature – named after Louis Néel, who had first identified this type of magnetic ordering.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] Above the Néel temperature, the material is typically paramagnetic.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] When no external field is applied, the antiferromagnetic structure corresponds to a vanishing total magnetization.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] In an external magnetic field, a kind of ferrimagnetic behavior may be displayed in the antiferromagnetic phase, with the absolute value of one of the sublattice magnetizations differing from that of the other sublattice, resulting in a nonzero net magnetization.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] Although the net magnetization should be zero at a temperature of absolute zero, the effect of spin canting often causes a small net magnetization to develop, as seen for example in hematite.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] The magnetic susceptibility of an antiferromagnetic material typically shows a maximum at the Néel temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] In contrast, at the transition between the ferromagnetic to the paramagnetic phases the susceptibility will diverge.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] In the antiferromagnetic case, a divergence is observed in the *staggered susceptibility*.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] Various microscopic (exchange) interactions between the magnetic moments or spins may lead to antiferromagnetic structures.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] In the simplest case, one may consider an Ising model on a bipartite lattice, e.g. the simple cubic lattice, with couplings between spins at nearest neighbor sites.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] Depending on the sign of that interaction, ferromagnetic or antiferromagnetic order will result.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] Geometrical frustration or competing ferro- and antiferromagnetic interactions may lead to different and, perhaps, more complicated magnetic structures.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] The relationship between magnetization and the magnetizing field is non-linear like in ferromagnetic materials.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] This fact is due to the contribution of the hysteresis loop, which for ferromagnetic materials involves a residual magnetization.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] Antiferromagnetic structures were first shown through neutron diffraction of transition metal oxides such as nickel, iron, and manganese oxides.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] The experiments, performed by Clifford Shull, gave the first results showing that magnetic dipoles could be oriented in an antiferromagnetic structure.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] Antiferromagnetic materials occur commonly among transition metal compounds, especially oxides.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] Examples include hematite, metals such as chromium, alloys such as iron manganese (FeMn), and oxides such as nickel oxide (NiO).
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] There are also numerous examples among high nuclearity metal clusters.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] Organic molecules can also exhibit antiferromagnetic coupling under rare circumstances, as seen in radicals such as 5-dehydro-m-xylylene.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] This provides the ability to "pin" the orientation of a ferromagnetic film, which provides one of the main uses in so-called spin valves, which are the basis of magnetic sensors including modern hard disk drive read heads.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] The temperature at or above which an antiferromagnetic layer loses its ability to "pin" the magnetization direction of an adjacent ferromagnetic layer is called the blocking temperature of that layer and is usually lower than the Néel temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] Unlike ferromagnetism, anti-ferromagnetic interactions can lead to multiple optimal states (ground states—states of minimal energy).
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] In one dimension, the anti-ferromagnetic ground state is an alternating series of spins: up, down, up, down, etc.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] Yet in two dimensions, multiple ground states can occur.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] Consider an equilateral triangle with three spins, one on each vertex.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] If each spin can take on only two values (up or down), there are 23 = 8 possible states of the system, six of which are ground states.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] The two situations which are not ground states are when all three spins are up or are all down.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] In any of the other six states, there will be two favorable interactions and one unfavorable one.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] This illustrates frustration: the inability of the system to find a single ground state.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] This type of magnetic behavior has been found in minerals that have a crystal stacking structure such as a Kagome lattice or hexagonal lattice.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] Synthetic antiferromagnets (often abbreviated by SAF) are artificial antiferromagnets consisting of two or more thin ferromagnetic layers separated by a nonmagnetic layer.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] Dipole coupling of the ferromagnetic layers results in antiparallel alignment of the magnetization of the ferromagnets.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] Antiferromagnetism plays a crucial role in devices employing giant magnetoresistance (GMR), an effect discovered in 1988 by the Nobel Prize winners Albert Fert and Peter Grünberg (awarded in 2007).
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] First, for antiferromagnets being employed as pinning layers and also since the original device design (iron-chromium-iron multilayer with the Cr layer thickness carefully tuned) amounts to a synthetic antiferromagnet.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] There are also examples of disordered materials (such as iron phosphate glasses) that become antiferromagnetic below their Néel temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] These disordered networks 'frustrate' the antiparallelism of adjacent spins; i.e. it is not possible to construct a network where each spin is surrounded by opposite neighbour spins.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] It can only be determined that the average correlation of neighbour spins is antiferromagnetic.
[src:magnetic-materials/antiferromagnetism] This type of magnetism is sometimes called speromagnetism.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Above the Curie temperature, the magnetic spins are randomly aligned in a paramagnet unless a magnetic field is applied.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] In physics and materials science, the **Curie temperature** (*T*C), or **Curie point**, is the temperature above which certain materials lose their permanent magnetic properties, which can (in most cases) be replaced by induced magnetism.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The Curie temperature is named after Pierre Curie, who showed that magnetism is lost at a critical temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The force of magnetism is determined by the magnetic moment, a dipole moment within an atom that originates from the angular momentum and spin of electrons.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Materials have different structures of intrinsic magnetic moments that depend on temperature; the Curie temperature is the critical point at which a material's intrinsic magnetic moments change direction.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Permanent magnetism is caused by the alignment of magnetic moments, and induced magnetism is created when disordered magnetic moments are forced to align in an applied magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] For example, the ordered magnetic moments (ferromagnetic, Figure 1) change and become disordered (paramagnetic, Figure 2) at the Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Higher temperatures make magnets weaker, as spontaneous magnetism only occurs below the Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Magnetic susceptibility above the Curie temperature can be calculated from the Curie–Weiss law, which is derived from Curie's law.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] In analogy to ferromagnetic and paramagnetic materials, the Curie temperature can also be used to describe the phase transition between ferroelectricity and paraelectricity.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] In this context, the order parameter is the *electric* polarization that goes from a finite value to zero when the temperature is increased above the Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] in 1895, Pierre Curie used strong magnets and precision balances to study the magnetic phase transition (now called the Curie point or Curie temperature).
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] In 1911, Pierre Weiss derived his Curie–Weiss law to explain this transition.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] At the atomic level, there are two contributors to the magnetic moment, the electron magnetic moment and the nuclear magnetic moment.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Of these two terms, the electron magnetic moment dominates, and the nuclear magnetic moment is insignificant.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] At higher temperatures, electrons have higher thermal energy.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] This has a randomizing effect on aligned magnetic domains, leading to the disruption of order, and the phenomenon of the Curie point.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Ferromagnetic, paramagnetic, ferrimagnetic, and antiferromagnetic materials have different intrinsic magnetic moment structures.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] At a material's specific Curie temperature (*T*C), these properties change.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The transition from antiferromagnetic to paramagnetic (or vice versa) occurs at the Néel temperature (*T*N), which is analogous to Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Ferromagnetic, paramagnetic, ferrimagnetic, and antiferromagnetic structures are made up of intrinsic magnetic moments.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] If all the electrons within the structure are paired, these moments cancel out due to their opposite spins and angular momenta.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Thus, even with an applied magnetic field, these materials have different properties and no Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] A material is paramagnetic only above its Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Paramagnetic materials are non-magnetic when a magnetic field is absent and magnetic when a magnetic field is applied.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] When a magnetic field is absent, the material has disordered magnetic moments; that is, the magnetic moments are asymmetrical and not aligned.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] When a magnetic field is present, the magnetic moments are temporarily realigned parallel to the applied field; the magnetic moments are symmetrical and aligned.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The magnetic moments being aligned in the same direction are what causes an induced magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] For paramagnetism, this response to an applied magnetic field is positive and is known as magnetic susceptibility.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The magnetic susceptibility only applies above the Curie temperature for disordered states.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Above the Curie temperature, the atoms are excited, and the spin orientations become randomized but can be realigned by an applied field, i.e., the material becomes paramagnetic.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Below the Curie temperature, the intrinsic structure has undergone a phase transition, the atoms are ordered, and the material is ferromagnetic.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The paramagnetic materials' induced magnetic fields are very weak compared with ferromagnetic materials' magnetic fields.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Materials are only ferromagnetic below their corresponding Curie temperatures.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Ferromagnetic materials are magnetic in the absence of an applied magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] When a magnetic field is absent the material has spontaneous magnetization which is a result of the ordered magnetic moments; that is, for ferromagnetism, the atoms are symmetrical and aligned in the same direction creating a permanent magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The magnetic interactions are held together by exchange interactions; otherwise thermal disorder would overcome the weak interactions of magnetic moments.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The exchange interaction has a zero probability of parallel electrons occupying the same point in time, implying a preferred parallel alignment in the material.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The Boltzmann factor contributes heavily as it prefers interacting particles to be aligned in the same direction.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] This causes ferromagnets to have strong magnetic fields and high Curie temperatures of around 1,000 K (730 °C).
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Below the Curie temperature, the atoms are aligned and parallel, causing spontaneous magnetism; the material is ferromagnetic.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Above the Curie temperature the material is paramagnetic, as the atoms lose their ordered magnetic moments when the material undergoes a phase transition.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Materials are only ferrimagnetic below their corresponding Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Ferrimagnetic materials are magnetic in the absence of an applied magnetic field and are made up of two different ions.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] As the magnetic moments are of different magnitudes in opposite directions there is still a spontaneous magnetism and a magnetic field is present.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Similar to ferromagnetic materials the magnetic interactions are held together by exchange interactions.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The orientations of moments however are anti-parallel which results in a net momentum by subtracting their momentum from one another.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Below the Curie temperature the atoms of each ion are aligned anti-parallel with different momentums causing a spontaneous magnetism; the material is ferrimagnetic.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Above the Curie temperature the material is paramagnetic as the atoms lose their ordered magnetic moments as the material undergoes a phase transition.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Materials are only antiferromagnetic below their corresponding **Néel temperature** or **magnetic ordering temperature**, *T*N.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] This is similar to the Curie temperature, since above the Néel temperature the material undergoes a phase transition and becomes paramagnetic.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] That is, the thermal energy becomes large enough to destroy the microscopic magnetic ordering within the material.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] It is named after Louis Néel (1904–2000), who received the 1970 Nobel Prize in Physics for his work in the area.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The material has equal magnetic moments aligned in opposite directions resulting in a zero magnetic moment and a net magnetism of zero at all temperatures below the Néel temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Antiferromagnetic materials are weakly magnetic in the absence or presence of an applied magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Similar to ferromagnetic materials the magnetic interactions are held together by exchange interactions preventing thermal disorder from overcoming the weak interactions of magnetic moments.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] When disorder occurs it is at the Néel temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The Curie–Weiss law is an adapted version of Curie's law.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The Curie–Weiss law is a simple model derived from a mean-field approximation, this means it works well for the materials temperature, T, much greater than their corresponding Curie temperature, *T*C, i.e.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] *T* ≫ *T*C; it however fails to describe the magnetic susceptibility, χ, in the immediate vicinity of the Curie point because of correlations in the fluctuations of neighboring magnetic moments.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Neither Curie's law nor the Curie–Weiss law holds for *T* < *T*C.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] λ is the Weiss molecular field constant.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] For full derivation see Curie–Weiss law.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] As the Curie–Weiss law is an approximation, a more accurate model is needed when the temperature, T, approaches the material's Curie temperature, *T*C.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Magnetic susceptibility occurs above the Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The critical exponent differs between materials and for the mean-field model is taken as γ = 1.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] As temperature is inversely proportional to magnetic susceptibility, when T approaches *T*C the denominator tends to zero and the magnetic susceptibility approaches infinity allowing magnetism to occur.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] This is a spontaneous magnetism which is a property of ferromagnetic and ferrimagnetic materials.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Magnetism depends on temperature and spontaneous magnetism occurs below the Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The critical exponent differs between materials and for the mean-field model as taken as β = ⁠1/2⁠ where *T* ≪ *T*C.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The spontaneous magnetism approaches zero as the temperature increases towards the materials Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The spontaneous magnetism, occurring in ferromagnetic, ferrimagnetic, and antiferromagnetic materials, approaches zero as the temperature increases towards the material's Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Spontaneous magnetism is at its maximum as the temperature approaches 0 K.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] That is, the magnetic moments are completely aligned and at their strongest magnitude of magnetism due to lack of thermal disturbance.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] In paramagnetic materials thermal energy is sufficient to overcome the ordered alignments.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] As the temperature approaches 0 K, the entropy decreases to zero, that is, the disorder decreases and the material becomes ordered.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] This occurs without the presence of an applied magnetic field and obeys the third law of thermodynamics.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Both Curie's law and the Curie–Weiss law fail as the temperature approaches 0 K.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] This is because they depend on the magnetic susceptibility, which only applies when the state is disordered.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Gadolinium sulfate continues to satisfy Curie's law at 1 K.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Between 0 and 1 K the law fails to hold and a sudden change in the intrinsic structure occurs at the Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The Ising model is mathematically based and can analyse the critical points of phase transitions in ferromagnetic order due to spins of electrons having magnitudes of ±⁠1/2⁠.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The spins interact with their neighbouring dipole electrons in the structure and here the Ising model can predict their behaviour with each other.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] This model is important for solving and understanding the concepts of phase transitions and hence solving the Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] As a result, many different dependencies that affect the Curie temperature can be analysed.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] For example, the surface and bulk properties depend on the alignment and magnitude of spins and the Ising model can determine the effects of magnetism in this system.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] One should note, in 1D the Curie (critical) temperature for a magnetic order phase transition is found to be at zero temperature, i.e. the magnetic order takes over only at T = 0.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Materials structures consist of intrinsic magnetic moments which are separated into domains called Weiss domains.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] This can result in ferromagnetic materials having no spontaneous magnetism as domains could potentially balance each other out.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The position of particles can therefore have different orientations around the surface than the main part (bulk) of the material.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] This property directly affects the Curie temperature as there can be a bulk Curie temperature *T*B and a different surface Curie temperature *T*S for a material.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] This allows for the surface Curie temperature to be ferromagnetic above the bulk Curie temperature when the main state is disordered, i.e. ordered and disordered states occur simultaneously.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The surface and bulk properties can be predicted by the Ising model and electron capture spectroscopy can be used to detect the electron spins and hence the magnetic moments on the surface of the material.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] An average total magnetism is taken from the bulk and surface temperatures to calculate the Curie temperature from the material, noting the bulk contributes more.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The angular momentum of an electron is either +⁠ħ/2⁠ or −⁠ħ/2⁠ due to it having a spin of ⁠1/2⁠, which gives a specific size of magnetic moment to the electron; the Bohr magneton.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Electrons orbiting around the nucleus in a current loop create a magnetic field which depends on the Bohr magneton and magnetic quantum number.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Therefore, the magnetic moments are related between angular and orbital momentum and affect each other.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Angular momentum contributes twice as much to magnetic moments than orbital.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] For terbium which is a rare-earth metal and has a high orbital angular momentum the magnetic moment is strong enough to affect the order above its bulk temperatures.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] It is said to have a high anisotropy on the surface, that is it is highly directed in one orientation.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The anisotropy in the bulk is different from its surface anisotropy just above these phase changes as the magnetic moments will be ordered differently or ordered in paramagnetic materials.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Composite materials, that is, materials composed from other materials with different properties, can change the Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] For example, a composite which has silver in it can create spaces for oxygen molecules in bonding which decreases the Curie temperature as the crystal lattice will not be as compact.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The alignment of magnetic moments in the composite material affects the Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] If the material's moments are parallel with each other, the Curie temperature will increase and if perpendicular the Curie temperature will decrease as either more or less thermal energy will be needed to destroy the alignments.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Preparing composite materials through different temperatures can result in different final compositions which will have different Curie temperatures.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Doping a material can also affect its Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The density of nanocomposite materials changes the Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Nanocomposites are compact structures on a nano-scale.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The structure is built up of high and low bulk Curie temperatures, however will only have one mean-field Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] A higher density of lower bulk temperatures results in a lower mean-field Curie temperature, and a higher density of higher bulk temperature significantly increases the mean-field Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] In more than one dimension the Curie temperature begins to increase as the magnetic moments will need more thermal energy to overcome the ordered structure.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The size of particles in a material's crystal lattice changes the Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Due to the small size of particles (nanoparticles) the fluctuations of electron spins become more prominent, which results in the Curie temperature drastically decreasing when the size of particles decreases, as the fluctuations cause disorder.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The size of a particle also affects the anisotropy causing alignment to become less stable and thus lead to disorder in magnetic moments.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The extreme of this is superparamagnetism which only occurs in small ferromagnetic particles.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] In this phenomenon, fluctuations are very influential causing magnetic moments to change direction randomly and thus create disorder.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] This is known as the coordination number which is the number of nearest neighbouring particles in a structure.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] This indicates a lower coordination number at the surface of a material than the bulk which leads to the surface becoming less significant when the temperature is approaching the Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] In smaller systems the coordination number for the surface is more significant and the magnetic moments have a stronger effect on the system.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Although fluctuations in particles can be minuscule, they are heavily dependent on the structure of crystal lattices as they react with their nearest neighbouring particles.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Fluctuations are also affected by the exchange interaction as parallel facing magnetic moments are favoured and therefore have less disturbance and disorder, therefore a tighter structure influences a stronger magnetism and therefore a higher Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Pressure changes a material's Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Increasing pressure on the crystal lattice decreases the volume of the system.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Pressure directly affects the kinetic energy in particles as movement increases causing the vibrations to disrupt the order of magnetic moments.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] This is similar to temperature as it also increases the kinetic energy of particles and destroys the order of magnetic moments and magnetism.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Pressure also affects the density of states (DOS).
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Here the DOS decreases causing the number of electrons available to the system to decrease.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] This leads to the number of magnetic moments decreasing as they depend on electron spins.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] It would be expected because of this that the Curie temperature would decrease; however, it increases.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] This is the result of the exchange interaction.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The exchange interaction favours the aligned parallel magnetic moments due to electrons being unable to occupy the same space in time and as this is increased due to the volume decreasing the Curie temperature increases with pressure.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The Curie temperature is made up of a combination of dependencies on kinetic energy and the DOS.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The concentration of particles also affects the Curie temperature when pressure is being applied and can result in a decrease in Curie temperature when the concentration is above a certain percent.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Orbital ordering changes the Curie temperature of a material.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Orbital ordering can be controlled through applied strains.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] This is a function that determines the wave of a single electron or paired electrons inside the material.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Having control over the probability of where the electron will be allows the Curie temperature to be altered.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] For example, the delocalised electrons can be moved onto the same plane by applied strains within the crystal lattice.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The Curie temperature is seen to increase greatly due to electrons being packed together in the same plane, they are forced to align due to the exchange interaction and thus increases the strength of the magnetic moments which prevents thermal disorder at lower temperatures.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] In analogy to ferromagnetic and paramagnetic materials, the term Curie temperature (*T*C) is also applied to the temperature at which a ferroelectric material transitions to being paraelectric.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Hence, *T*C is the temperature where ferroelectric materials lose their spontaneous polarisation as a first or second order phase change occurs.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] In case of a second order transition, the Curie Weiss temperature *T*0 which defines the maximum of the dielectric constant is equal to the Curie temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] However, the Curie temperature can be 10 K higher than *T*0 in case of a first order transition.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Materials are only ferroelectric below their corresponding transition temperature *T*0.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Ferroelectric materials are all pyroelectric and therefore have a spontaneous electric polarisation as the structures are unsymmetrical.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Ferroelectric materials' polarization is subject to hysteresis (Figure 4); that is they are dependent on their past state as well as their current state.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] As an electric field is applied the dipoles are forced to align and polarisation is created, when the electric field is removed polarisation remains.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] The hysteresis loop depends on temperature and as a result as the temperature is increased and reaches *T*0 the two curves become one curve as shown in the dielectric polarisation (Figure 5).
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] A heat-induced ferromagnetic-paramagnetic transition is used in magneto-optical storage media for erasing and writing of new data.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Famous examples include the Sony Minidisc format as well as the now-obsolete CD-MO format.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Curie point electro-magnets have been proposed and tested for actuation mechanisms in passive safety systems of fast breeder reactors, where control rods are dropped into the reactor core if the actuation mechanism heats up beyond the material's Curie point.
[src:magnetic-materials/curie-temperature] Other uses include temperature control in soldering irons and stabilizing the magnetic field of tachometer generators against temperature variation.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Magnetic permeability describes the induced magnetization of a material due to the presence of an external magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] For example, this temporary magnetization inside a steel plate accounts for the plate's attraction to a magnet.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Whether or not that steel plate then acquires permanent magnetization depends on both the strength of the applied field and on the coercivity of that particular piece of steel (which varies with the steel's chemical composition and any heat treatment it may have undergone).
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] In physics, multiple types of material magnetism have been distinguished.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Ferromagnetism (along with the similar effect ferrimagnetism) is the strongest type and is responsible for the common phenomenon of everyday magnetism.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] A common example of a permanent magnet is a refrigerator magnet.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Substances respond weakly to magnetic fields by three other types of magnetism—paramagnetism, diamagnetism, and antiferromagnetism—but the forces are usually so weak that they can only be detected by lab instruments.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Permanent magnets (materials that can be magnetized by an external magnetic field and remain magnetized after the external field is removed) are either ferromagnetic or ferrimagnetic, as are the materials that are strongly attracted to them.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Relatively few materials are ferromagnetic; the common ones are the metals iron, cobalt, nickel and most of their alloys, and certain rare-earth metals.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Ferromagnetic materials can be divided into magnetically "soft" materials (like annealed iron) having low coercivity, which do not tend to stay magnetized, and magnetically "hard" materials having high coercivity, which do.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] To demagnetize a saturated magnet, a magnetic field must be applied.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] The threshold at which demagnetization occurs depends on the coercivity of the material.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] The overall strength of a magnet is measured by its magnetic moment or, alternatively, its total magnetic flux.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] The local strength of magnetism in a material is measured by its magnetization.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Historically, the term *ferromagnetism* was used for any material that could exhibit spontaneous magnetization: a net magnetic moment in the absence of an external magnetic field; that is, any material that could become a magnet.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] In a landmark paper in 1948, Louis Néel showed that spontaneous magnetization can arise from two distinct types of magnetic ordering.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] In ferromagnetism in the strict sense, magnetic moments align parallel to one another.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] In *ferrimagnetism*, magnetic moments are arranged in two antiparallel sublattices with different magnitudes, resulting in a net magnetization.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] When the opposing moments are equal in magnitude and cancel completely, the alignment is known as *antiferromagnetism*; such materials do not exhibit spontaneous magnetization.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Ferromagnetism is an unusual property that occurs in only a few substances.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] The common ones are the transition metals iron, nickel, and cobalt, as well as their alloys and alloys of rare-earth metals.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] It is a property not just of the chemical make-up of a material, but of its crystalline structure and microstructure.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Ferromagnetism results from these materials having many unpaired electrons in their d-block (in the case of iron and its relatives) or f-block (in the case of the rare-earth metals), a result of Hund's rule of maximum multiplicity.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] There are ferromagnetic metal alloys whose constituents are not themselves ferromagnetic, called Heusler alloys, named after Fritz Heusler.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Conversely, there are non-magnetic alloys, such as types of stainless steel, composed almost exclusively of ferromagnetic metals.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Amorphous (non-crystalline) ferromagnetic metallic alloys are sometimes called asperomagnets.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] These can be made by very rapid quenching (cooling) of an alloy.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] These have the advantage that their properties are nearly isotropic (not aligned along a crystal axis); this results in low coercivity, low hysteresis loss, high permeability, and high electrical resistivity.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] One such typical material is a transition metal-metalloid alloy, made from about 80% transition metal (usually Fe, Co, or Ni) and a metalloid component (B, C, Si, P, or Al) that lowers the melting point.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] A relatively new class of exceptionally strong ferromagnetic materials are the rare-earth magnets.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] They contain lanthanide elements that are known for their ability to carry large magnetic moments in well-localized f-orbitals.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] The table lists a selection of ferromagnetic and ferrimagnetic compounds, along with their Curie temperature (*T*C), above which they cease to exhibit spontaneous magnetization.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Most ferromagnetic materials are metals, since the conducting electrons are often responsible for mediating the ferromagnetic interactions.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] It is therefore a challenge to develop ferromagnetic insulators, especially multiferroic materials, which are both ferromagnetic and ferroelectric.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] A number of actinide compounds are ferromagnets at room temperature or exhibit ferromagnetism upon cooling.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] PuP is a paramagnet with cubic symmetry at room temperature, but which undergoes a structural transition into a tetragonal state with ferromagnetic order when cooled below its *T*C = 125 K.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] In its ferromagnetic state, PuP's easy axis is in the ⟨100⟩ direction.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Above *T*C ≈ 500 K, NpFe2 is also paramagnetic and cubic.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Cooling below the Curie temperature produces a rhombohedral distortion wherein the rhombohedral angle changes from 60° (cubic phase) to 60.53°.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] An alternate description of this distortion is to consider the length c along the unique trigonal axis (after the distortion has begun) and a as the distance in the plane perpendicular to c.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] In the cubic phase this reduces to c/a = 1.00.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] which is the largest strain in any actinide compound.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] NpNi2 undergoes a similar lattice distortion below *T*C = 32 K, with a strain of (43 ± 5) × 10−4.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] In 2009, a team of MIT physicists demonstrated that a lithium gas cooled to less than one kelvin can exhibit ferromagnetism.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] The team cooled fermionic lithium-6 to less than 150 nK (150 billionths of one kelvin) using infrared laser cooling.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] This demonstration is the first time that ferromagnetism has been demonstrated in a gas.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] In rare circumstances, ferromagnetism can be observed in compounds consisting of only s-block and p-block elements, such as rubidium sesquioxide.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] In 2018, a team of University of Minnesota physicists demonstrated that body-centered tetragonal ruthenium exhibits ferromagnetism at room temperature.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Recent research has shown evidence that ferromagnetism can be induced in some materials by an electric current or voltage.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Antiferromagnetic LaMnO3 and SrCoO have been switched to be ferromagnetic by a current.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] In July 2020, scientists reported inducing ferromagnetism in the abundant diamagnetic material iron pyrite ("fool's gold") by an applied voltage.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] In these experiments, the ferromagnetism was limited to a thin surface layer.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] The Bohr–Van Leeuwen theorem, discovered in the 1910s, showed that classical physics theories are unable to account for any form of material magnetism, including ferromagnetism; the explanation rather depends on the quantum mechanical description of atoms.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Each of an atom's electrons has a magnetic moment according to its spin state, as described by quantum mechanics.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] The Pauli exclusion principle, also a consequence of quantum mechanics, restricts the occupancy of electrons' spin states in atomic orbitals, generally causing the magnetic moments from an atom's electrons to largely or completely cancel.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] An atom will have a *net* magnetic moment when that cancellation is incomplete.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] One of the fundamental properties of an electron (besides that it carries charge) is that it has a magnetic dipole moment, i.e., it behaves like a tiny magnet, producing a magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] This dipole moment comes from a more fundamental property of the electron: its quantum mechanical spin.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Due to its quantum nature, the spin of the electron can be in one of only two states, with the magnetic field either pointing "up" or "down" (for any choice of up and down).
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Electron spin in atoms is the main source of ferromagnetism, although there is also a contribution from the orbital angular momentum of the electron about the nucleus.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] When these magnetic dipoles in a piece of matter are aligned (point in the same direction), their individually tiny magnetic fields add together to create a much larger macroscopic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] However, materials made of atoms with filled electron shells have a total dipole moment of zero: because the electrons all exist in pairs with opposite spin, every electron's magnetic moment is cancelled by the opposite moment of the second electron in the pair.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Only atoms with partially filled shells (i.e., unpaired spins) can have a net magnetic moment, so ferromagnetism occurs only in materials with partially filled shells.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Because of Hund's rules, the first few electrons in an otherwise unoccupied shell tend to have the same spin, thereby increasing the total dipole moment.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] These unpaired dipoles (often called simply "spins", even though they also generally include orbital angular momentum) tend to align in parallel to an external magnetic field – leading to a macroscopic effect called paramagnetism.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] In ferromagnetism, however, the magnetic interaction between neighboring atoms' magnetic dipoles is strong enough that they align with *each other* regardless of any applied field, resulting in the spontaneous magnetization of so-called domains.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] This results in the large observed magnetic permeability of ferromagnetics, and the ability of magnetically hard materials to form permanent magnets.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] When two nearby atoms have unpaired electrons, whether the electron spins are parallel or antiparallel affects whether the electrons can share the same orbit as a result of the quantum mechanical effect called the exchange interaction.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] This in turn affects the electron location and the Coulomb (electrostatic) interaction and thus the energy difference between these states.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] The exchange interaction is related to the Pauli exclusion principle, which says that two electrons with the same spin cannot also be in the same spatial state (orbital).
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] This is a consequence of the spin–statistics theorem and that electrons are fermions.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Therefore, under certain conditions, when the orbitals of the unpaired outer valence electrons from adjacent atoms overlap, the distributions of their electric charge in space are farther apart when the electrons have parallel spins than when they have opposite spins.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] This reduces the electrostatic energy of the electrons when their spins are parallel compared to their energy when the spins are antiparallel, so the parallel-spin state is more stable.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] This difference in energy is called the exchange energy.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] In simple terms, the outer electrons of adjacent atoms, which repel each other, can move further apart by aligning their spins in the same direction.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] This energy difference can be orders of magnitude larger than the energy differences associated with the magnetic dipole–dipole interaction due to dipole orientation, which tends to align the dipoles antiparallel.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] In certain doped semiconductor oxides, RKKY interactions have been shown to bring about periodic longer-range magnetic interactions, a phenomenon of significance in the study of spintronic materials.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] The materials in which the exchange interaction is much stronger than the competing dipole–dipole interaction are frequently called *magnetic materials*.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] For instance, in iron (Fe) the exchange force is about 1,000 times stronger than the dipole interaction.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Therefore, below the Curie temperature, virtually all of the dipoles in a ferromagnetic material will be aligned.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] In addition to ferromagnetism, the exchange interaction is also responsible for the other types of spontaneous ordering of atomic magnetic moments occurring in magnetic solids: antiferromagnetism and ferrimagnetism.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] There are different exchange interaction mechanisms which create the magnetism in different ferromagnetic, ferrimagnetic, and antiferromagnetic substances—these mechanisms include direct exchange, RKKY exchange, double exchange, and superexchange.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Although the exchange interaction keeps spins aligned, it does not align them in a particular direction.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Without magnetic anisotropy, the spins in a magnet randomly change direction in response to thermal fluctuations, and the magnet is superparamagnetic.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] There are several kinds of magnetic anisotropy, the most common of which is magnetocrystalline anisotropy.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] This is a dependence of the energy on the direction of magnetization relative to the crystallographic lattice.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Another common source of anisotropy, inverse magnetostriction, is induced by internal strains.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Single-domain magnets also can have a *shape anisotropy* due to the magnetostatic effects of the particle shape.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] As the temperature of a magnet increases, the anisotropy tends to decrease, and there is often a blocking temperature at which a transition to superparamagnetism occurs.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] The spontaneous alignment of magnetic dipoles in ferromagnetic materials would seem to suggest that every piece of ferromagnetic material should have a strong magnetic field, since all the spins are aligned; yet iron and other ferromagnets are often found in an "unmagnetized" state.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] This is because a bulk piece of ferromagnetic material is divided into tiny regions called *magnetic domains* (also known as *Weiss domains*).
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Within each domain, the spins are aligned, but if the bulk material is in its lowest energy configuration (i.e.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] "unmagnetized"), the spins of separate domains point in different directions and their magnetic fields cancel out, so the bulk material has no net large-scale magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Ferromagnetic materials spontaneously divide into magnetic domains because the exchange interaction is a short-range force, so over long distances of many atoms, the tendency of the magnetic dipoles to reduce their energy by orienting in opposite directions wins out.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] If all the dipoles in a piece of ferromagnetic material are aligned parallel, it creates a large magnetic field extending into the space around it.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] This contains a lot of magnetostatic energy.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] The material can reduce this energy by splitting into many domains pointing in different directions, so the magnetic field is confined to small local fields in the material, reducing the volume of the field.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] The domains are separated by thin domain walls a number of molecules thick, in which the direction of magnetization of the dipoles rotates smoothly from one domain's direction to the other.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Thus, a piece of iron in its lowest energy state ("unmagnetized") generally has little or no net magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] However, the magnetic domains in a material are not fixed in place; they are simply regions where the spins of the electrons have aligned spontaneously due to their magnetic fields, and thus can be altered by an external magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] The domains will remain aligned when the external field is removed, and sum to create a magnetic field of their own extending into the space around the material, thus creating a "permanent" magnet.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] The domains do not go back to their original minimum energy configuration when the field is removed because the domain walls tend to become 'pinned' or 'snagged' on defects in the crystal lattice, preserving their parallel orientation.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] This is shown by the Barkhausen effect: as the magnetizing field is changed, the material's magnetization changes in thousands of tiny discontinuous jumps as domain walls suddenly "snap" past defects.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] This magnetization as a function of an external field is described by a hysteresis curve.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Although this state of aligned domains found in a piece of magnetized ferromagnetic material is not a minimal-energy configuration, it is metastable, and can persist for long periods, as shown by samples of magnetite from the sea floor which have maintained their magnetization for millions of years.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Commercial magnets are made of "hard" ferromagnetic or ferrimagnetic materials with very large magnetic anisotropy such as alnico and ferrites, which have a very strong tendency for the magnetization to be pointed along one axis of the crystal, the "easy axis".
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] During manufacture the materials are subjected to various metallurgical processes in a powerful magnetic field, which aligns the crystal grains so their "easy" axes of magnetization all point in the same direction.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Thus, the magnetization, and the resulting magnetic field, is "built in" to the crystal structure of the material, making it very difficult to demagnetize.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] As the temperature of a material increases, thermal motion, or entropy, competes with the ferromagnetic tendency for dipoles to align.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] Below that temperature, there is a spontaneous symmetry breaking and magnetic moments become aligned with their neighbors.
[src:magnetic-materials/ferromagnetism] The Curie temperature itself is a critical point, where the magnetic susceptibility is theoretically infinite and, although there is no net magnetization, domain-like spin correlations fluctuate at all length scales.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteresis can be found in physics, chemistry, engineering, biology, and economics.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] It is incorporated in many artificial systems: for example, in thermostats and Schmitt triggers, it prevents unwanted frequent switching.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteresis can be a dynamic lag between an input and an output that disappears if the input is varied more slowly; this is known as *rate-dependent* hysteresis.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] However, phenomena such as the magnetic hysteresis loops are mainly *rate-independent*, which makes a durable memory possible.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Systems with hysteresis are nonlinear, and can be mathematically challenging to model.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Some hysteretic models, such as the Preisach model (originally applied to ferromagnetism) and the Bouc–Wen model, attempt to capture general features of hysteresis; and there are also phenomenological models for particular phenomena such as the Jiles–Atherton model for ferromagnetism.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] It is difficult to define hysteresis precisely.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Mayergoyz wrote "...the very meaning of hysteresis varies from one area to another, from paper to paper and from author to author.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] As a result, a stringent mathematical definition of hysteresis is needed in order to avoid confusion and ambiguity.".
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The term "hysteresis" is derived from ὑστέρησις, an Ancient Greek word meaning "deficiency" or "lagging behind".
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] It was coined in 1881 by Sir James Alfred Ewing to describe the behaviour of magnetic materials.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Some early work on describing hysteresis in mechanical systems was performed by James Clerk Maxwell.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Subsequently, hysteretic models have received significant attention in the works of Ferenc Preisach (Preisach model of hysteresis), Louis Néel and Douglas Hugh Everett in connection with magnetism and absorption.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] A more formal mathematical theory of systems with hysteresis was developed in the 1970s by a group of Russian mathematicians led by Mark Krasnosel'skii.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] One type of hysteresis is a lag between input and output.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] where $\chi _{\text{i}}$ is the instantaneous response and $\Phi _{d}(\tau )$ is the impulse response to an impulse that occurred $\tau$ time units in the past.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In the frequency domain, input and output are related by a complex *generalized susceptibility* that can be computed from $\Phi _{d}$ ; it is mathematically equivalent to a transfer function in linear filter theory and analogue signal processing.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This kind of hysteresis is often referred to as *rate-dependent hysteresis*.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] If the input is reduced to zero, the output continues to respond for a finite time.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This constitutes a memory of the past, but a limited one because it disappears as the output decays to zero.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The phase lag depends on the frequency of the input, and goes to zero as the frequency decreases.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] When rate-dependent hysteresis is due to dissipative effects like friction, it is associated with power loss.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Systems with *rate-independent hysteresis* have a *persistent* memory of the past that remains after the transients have died out.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The future development of such a system depends on the history of states visited, but does not fade as the events recede into the past.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] If an input variable *X(t)* cycles from *X*0 to *X*1 and back again, the output *Y(t)* may be *Y*0 initially but a different value *Y*2 upon return.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The values of *Y(t)* depend on the path of values that *X(t)* passes through but not on the speed at which it traverses the path.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Many authors restrict the term hysteresis to mean only rate-independent hysteresis.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteresis effects can be characterized using the Preisach model and the generalized Prandtl−Ishlinskii model.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In control systems, hysteresis can be used to filter signals so that the output reacts less rapidly than it otherwise would by taking recent system history into account.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] For example, a thermostat controlling a heater may switch the heater on when the temperature drops below A, but not turn it off until the temperature rises above B.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] (For instance, if one wishes to maintain a temperature of 20 °C then one might set the thermostat to turn the heater on when the temperature drops to below 18 °C and off when the temperature exceeds 22 °C).
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Similarly, a pressure switch can be designed to exhibit hysteresis, with pressure set-points substituted for temperature thresholds.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Often, some amount of hysteresis is intentionally added to an electronic circuit to prevent unwanted rapid switching.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This and similar techniques are used to compensate for contact bounce in switches, or noise in an electrical signal.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] A Schmitt trigger is a simple electronic circuit that exhibits this property.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] A latching relay uses a solenoid to actuate a ratcheting mechanism that keeps the relay closed even if power to the relay is terminated.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Some positive feedback from the output to one input of a comparator can increase the natural hysteresis (a function of its gain) it exhibits.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteresis is essential to the workings of some memristors (circuit components which "remember" changes in the current passing through them by changing their resistance).
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteresis can be used when connecting arrays of elements such as nanoelectronics, electrochrome cells and memory effect devices using passive matrix addressing.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Shortcuts are made between adjacent components (see crosstalk) and the hysteresis helps to keep the components in a particular state while the other components change states.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Thus, all rows can be addressed at the same time instead of individually.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In the field of audio electronics, a noise gate often implements hysteresis intentionally to prevent the gate from "chattering" when signals close to its threshold are applied.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] A hysteresis is sometimes intentionally added to computer algorithms.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The field of user interface design has borrowed the term hysteresis to refer to times when the state of the user interface intentionally lags behind the apparent user input.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] For example, a menu that was drawn in response to a mouse-over event may remain on-screen for a brief moment after the mouse has moved out of the trigger region and the menu region.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This allows the user to move the mouse directly to an item on the menu, even if part of that direct mouse path is outside of both the trigger region and the menu region.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] For instance, right-clicking on the desktop in most Windows interfaces will create a menu that exhibits this behavior.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In aerodynamics, hysteresis can be observed when decreasing the angle of attack of a wing after stall, regarding the lift and drag coefficients.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The angle of attack at which the flow on top of the wing reattaches is generally lower than the angle of attack at which the flow separates during the increase of the angle of attack.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteresis can be observed in the stage-flow relationship of a river during rapidly changing conditions such as passing of a flood wave.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] It is most pronounced in low gradient streams with steep leading edge hydrographs.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Moving parts within machines, such as the components of a gear train, normally have a small gap between them, to allow movement and lubrication.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] As a consequence of this gap, any reversal in direction of a drive part will not be passed on immediately to the driven part.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This unwanted delay is normally kept as small as practicable, and is usually called backlash.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The amount of backlash will increase with time as the surfaces of moving parts wear.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In the elastic hysteresis of rubber, the area in the centre of a hysteresis loop is the energy dissipated due to material internal friction.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Elastic hysteresis was one of the first types of hysteresis to be examined.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The effect can be demonstrated using a rubber band with weights attached to it.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] If the top of a rubber band is hung on a hook and small weights are attached to the bottom of the band one at a time, it will stretch and get longer.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] As more weights are *loaded* onto it, the band will continue to stretch because the force the weights are exerting on the band is increasing.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] When each weight is taken off, or *unloaded*, the band will contract as the force is reduced.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] As the weights are taken off, each weight that produced a specific length as it was loaded onto the band now contracts less, resulting in a slightly longer length as it is unloaded.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This is because the band does not obey Hooke's law perfectly.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The hysteresis loop of an idealized rubber band is shown in the figure.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In terms of force, the rubber band was harder to stretch when it was being loaded than when it was being unloaded.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In terms of time, when the band is unloaded, the effect (the length) lagged behind the cause (the force of the weights) because the length has not yet reached the value it had for the same weight during the loading part of the cycle.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In terms of energy, more energy was required during the loading than the unloading, the excess energy being dissipated as thermal energy.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Elastic hysteresis is more pronounced when the loading and unloading is done quickly than when it is done slowly.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Some materials such as hard metals don't show elastic hysteresis under a moderate load, whereas other hard materials like granite and marble do.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Materials such as rubber exhibit a high degree of elastic hysteresis.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] When the intrinsic hysteresis of rubber is being measured, the material can be considered to behave like a gas.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] When a rubber band is stretched, it heats up, and if it is suddenly released, it cools down perceptibly.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] These effects correspond to a large hysteresis from the thermal exchange with the environment and a smaller hysteresis due to internal friction within the rubber.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This proper, intrinsic hysteresis can be measured only if the rubber band is thermally isolated.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Small vehicle suspensions using rubber (or other elastomers) can achieve the dual function of springing and damping because rubber, unlike metal springs, has pronounced hysteresis and does not return all the absorbed compression energy on the rebound.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Mountain bikes have made use of elastomer suspension, as did the original Mini car.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The primary cause of rolling resistance when a body (such as a ball, tire, or wheel) rolls on a surface is hysteresis.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This is attributed to the viscoelastic characteristics of the material of the rolling body.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The contact angle formed between a liquid and solid phase will exhibit a range of contact angles that are possible.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] There are two common methods for measuring this range of contact angles.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The first method is referred to as the tilting base method.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Once a drop is dispensed on the surface with the surface level, the surface is then tilted from 0° to 90°.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] As the drop is tilted, the downhill side will be in a state of imminent wetting while the uphill side will be in a state of imminent dewetting.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] As the tilt increases the downhill contact angle will increase and represents the advancing contact angle while the uphill side will decrease; this is the receding contact angle.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The values for these angles just prior to the drop releasing will typically represent the advancing and receding contact angles.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The difference between these two angles is the contact angle hysteresis.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The second method is often referred to as the add/remove volume method.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] When the maximum liquid volume is removed from the drop without the interfacial area decreasing the receding contact angle is thus measured.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] When volume is added to the maximum before the interfacial area increases, this is the advancing contact angle.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] As with the tilt method, the difference between the advancing and receding contact angles is the contact angle hysteresis.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Most researchers prefer the tilt method; the add/remove method requires that a tip or needle stay embedded in the drop which can affect the accuracy of the values, especially the receding contact angle.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The bubble shape hysteresis is a consequence of gas compressibility, which causes the bubbles to behave differently across expansion and contraction.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] During expansion, bubbles undergo large non equilibrium jumps in volume, while during contraction the bubbles are more stable and undergo a relatively smaller jump in volume resulting in an asymmetry across expansion and contraction.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The bubble shape hysteresis is qualitatively similar to the adsorption hysteresis, and as in the contact angle hysteresis, the interfacial properties play an important role in bubble shape hysteresis.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The existence of the bubble shape hysteresis has important consequences in interfacial rheology experiments involving bubbles.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] As a result of the hysteresis, not all sizes of the bubbles can be formed on a capillary.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Further the gas compressibility causing the hysteresis leads to unintended complications in the phase relation between the applied changes in interfacial area to the expected interfacial stresses.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] These difficulties can be avoided by designing experimental systems to avoid the bubble shape hysteresis.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteresis can also occur during physical adsorption processes.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In this type of hysteresis, the quantity adsorbed is different when gas is being added than it is when being removed.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The specific causes of adsorption hysteresis are still an active area of research, but it is linked to differences in the nucleation and evaporation mechanisms inside mesopores.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] These mechanisms are further complicated by effects such as cavitation and pore blocking.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In physical adsorption, hysteresis is evidence of mesoporosity-indeed, the definition of mesopores (2–50 nm) is associated with the appearance (50 nm) and disappearance (2 nm) of mesoporosity in nitrogen adsorption isotherms as a function of Kelvin radius.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] An adsorption isotherm showing hysteresis is said to be of Type IV (for a wetting adsorbate) or Type V (for a non-wetting adsorbate), and hysteresis loops themselves are classified according to how symmetric the loop is.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Adsorption hysteresis loops also have the unusual property that it is possible to scan within a hysteresis loop by reversing the direction of adsorption while on a point on the loop.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The resulting scans are called "crossing", "converging", or "returning", depending on the shape of the isotherm at this point.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The relationship between matric water potential and water content is the basis of the water retention curve.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Matric potential measurements (Ψm) are converted to volumetric water content (θ) measurements based on a site or soil specific calibration curve.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteresis is a source of water content measurement error.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Matric potential hysteresis arises from differences in wetting behaviour causing dry medium to re-wet; that is, it depends on the saturation history of the porous medium.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteretic behaviour means that, for example, at a matric potential (Ψm) of 5 kPa, the volumetric water content (θ) of a fine sandy soil matrix could be anything between 8% and 25%.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Tensiometers are directly influenced by this type of hysteresis.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Two other types of sensors used to measure soil water matric potential are also influenced by hysteresis effects within the sensor itself.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Resistance blocks, both nylon and gypsum based, measure matric potential as a function of electrical resistance.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The relation between the sensor's electrical resistance and sensor matric potential is hysteretic.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Thermocouples measure matric potential as a function of heat dissipation.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteresis occurs because measured heat dissipation depends on sensor water content, and the sensor water content–matric potential relationship is hysteretic.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] As of 2002, only desorption curves are usually measured during calibration of soil moisture sensors.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Despite the fact that it can be a source of significant error, the sensor specific effect of hysteresis is generally ignored.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] When an external magnetic field is applied to a ferromagnetic material such as iron, the atomic domains align themselves with it.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Even when the field is removed, part of the alignment will be retained: the material has become *magnetized*.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Once magnetized, the magnet will stay magnetized indefinitely.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] To demagnetize it requires heat or a magnetic field in the opposite direction.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This is the effect that provides the element of memory in a hard disk drive.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The relationship between field strength *H* and magnetization *M* is not linear in such materials.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] If a magnet is demagnetized (*H = M = 0*) and the relationship between *H* and *M* is plotted for increasing levels of field strength, *M* follows the *initial magnetization curve*.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This curve increases rapidly at first and then approaches an asymptote called magnetic saturation.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] If the magnetic field is now reduced monotonically, *M* follows a different curve.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] At zero field strength, the magnetization is offset from the origin by an amount called the remanence.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] If the *H-M* relationship is plotted for all strengths of applied magnetic field the result is a hysteresis loop called the *main loop*.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The width of the middle section is twice the coercivity of the material.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] A closer look at a magnetization curve generally reveals a series of small, random jumps in magnetization called Barkhausen jumps.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This effect is due to crystallographic defects such as dislocations.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Magnetic hysteresis loops are not exclusive to materials with ferromagnetic ordering.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Other magnetic orderings, such as spin glass ordering, also exhibit this phenomenon.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The phenomenon of hysteresis in ferromagnetic materials is the result of two effects: rotation of magnetization and changes in size or number of magnetic domains.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In general, the magnetization varies (in direction but not magnitude) across a magnet, but in sufficiently small magnets, it does not.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In these single-domain magnets, the magnetization responds to a magnetic field by rotating.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Single-domain magnets are used wherever a strong, stable magnetization is needed (for example, magnetic recording).
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Larger magnets are divided into regions called *domains*.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Across each domain, the magnetization does not vary; but between domains are relatively thin *domain walls* in which the direction of magnetization rotates from the direction of one domain to another.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] If the magnetic field changes, the walls move, changing the relative sizes of the domains.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Because the domains are not magnetized in the same direction, the magnetic moment per unit volume is smaller than it would be in a single-domain magnet; but domain walls involve rotation of only a small part of the magnetization, so it is much easier to change the magnetic moment.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The magnetization can also change by addition or subtraction of domains (called *nucleation* and *denucleation*).
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The most known empirical models in hysteresis are Preisach and Jiles-Atherton models.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] These models allow an accurate modeling of the hysteresis loop and are widely used in the industry.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] However, these models lose the connection with thermodynamics and the energy consistency is not ensured.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] A more recent model, with a more consistent thermodynamical foundation, is the vectorial incremental nonconservative consistent hysteresis (VINCH) model of Lavet et al.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] There are a great variety of applications of the hysteresis in ferromagnets.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Many of these make use of their ability to retain a memory, for example magnetic tape, hard disks, and credit cards.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In these applications, *hard* magnets (high coercivity) like iron are desirable, such that as much energy is absorbed as possible during the write operation and the resultant magnetized information is not easily erased.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] On the other hand, magnetically *soft* (low coercivity) iron is used for the cores in electromagnets.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The low coercivity minimizes the energy loss associated with hysteresis, as the magnetic field periodically reverses in the presence of an alternating current.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The low energy loss during a hysteresis loop is the reason why soft iron is used for transformer cores and electric motors.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Electrical hysteresis typically occurs in ferroelectric material, where domains of polarization contribute to the total polarization.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Polarization is the electrical dipole moment (either C·m−2 or C·m).
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The mechanism, an organization of the polarization into domains, is similar to that of magnetic hysteresis.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteresis manifests itself in state transitions when melting temperature and freezing temperature do not agree.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] For example, agar melts at 85 °C (185 °F) and solidifies from 32 to 40 °C (90 to 104 °F).
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This is to say that once agar is melted at 85 °C, it retains a liquid state until cooled to 40 °C.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Therefore, from the temperatures of 40 to 85 °C, agar can be either solid or liquid, depending on which state it was before.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteresis in cell biology often follows bistable systems where the same input state can lead to two different, stable outputs.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Where bistability can lead to digital, switch-like outputs from the continuous inputs of chemical concentrations and activities, hysteresis makes these systems more resistant to noise.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] These systems are often characterized by higher values of the input required to switch into a particular state as compared to the input required to stay in the state, allowing for a transition that is not continuously reversible, and thus less susceptible to noise.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In the case of mitosis, irreversibility is essential to maintain the overall integrity of the system such that we have three designated checkpoints to account for this: G1/S, G2/M, and the spindle checkpoint.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Irreversible hysteresis in this context ensures that once a cell commits to a specific phase (e.g., entering mitosis or DNA replication), it does not revert to a previous phase, even if conditions or regulatory signals change.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Based on the irreversible hysteresis curve, there does exist an input at which the cell jumps to the next stable state, but there is no input that allows the cell to revert to its previous stable state, even when the input is 0, demonstrating irreversibility.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Positive feedback is critical for generating hysteresis in the cell cycle.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] For example: In the G2/M transition, active CDK1 promotes the activation of more CDK1 molecules by inhibiting Wee1 (an inhibitor) and activating Cdc25 (a phosphatase that activates CDK1).
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] These loops lock the cell into its current state and amplify the activation of CDK1.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Positive feedback also serves to create a bistable system where CDK1 is either fully inactivated or fully activated.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteresis prevents the cell from oscillating between these two states from small perturbations in signal (input).
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] A biochemical system that is under the control of reversible hysteresis has both forward and reverse trajectories.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The system generally requires a higher [input] to proceed forward into the next bistable state then to exit from that stage.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] For example, cells undergoing cell division exhibit reversible hysteresis in that it takes a higher concentration of cyclins to switch them from G2 phase into mitosis than to stay in mitosis once begun.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Additionally, because the [cyclin] required to reverse the cell back to the G2 phase is much lower than the [cyclin] to enter mitosis, this improved the bistability of mitosis because it is more resistance to weak or transient signals.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Small perturbations the [input] will be unable to push the cell out of mitosis so easily.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In systems with bistability, the same input level can correspond to two distinct stable states (e.g., "low output" and "high output").
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The actual state of the system depends on its history –whether the input level was increasing (forward trajectory) or decreasing (backward trajectory).
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Thus, it is difficult to determine which state a cell is in if given only a bistability curve.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The cell's ability to "remember" its prior state ensures stability and prevents it from switching states unnecessarily due to minor fluctuations in input.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This memory is often maintained through molecular feedback loops, such as positive feedback in signaling pathways, or the persistence of regulatory molecules like proteins or phosphorylated components.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] For example, the refractory period in action potentials is primarily controlled by history.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Absolute refraction period prevents a volted-gated sodium channel from activating or refiring after it has just fired.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This is because following the absolute refractory period, the neuron is less excitable due to hyperpolarization caused by potassium efflux.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This molecular inhibitory feedback creates a memory for the neuron or cell, so that the neuron does not fire too soon.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] As time passes, the neuron or cell will slowly lose the memory of having fired and will begin to fire again.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Thus, memory is time-dependent, which is important in maintaining homeostasis and regulating many different biological processes.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Cells advancing through the cell cycle must make an irreversible commitment to mitosis, ensuring they do not revert to interphase before successfully segregating their chromosomes.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] A mathematical model of cell-cycle progression in cell-free egg extracts from frogs suggests that hysteresis in the molecular control system drives these irreversible transitions into and out of mitosis.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Here, Cdc2 (Cyclin-dependent kinase 1 or CDK1) is responsible for mitotic entry and exit such that binding of cyclin B forms a complex called Maturation-Promoting Factor (MPF).
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The activation threshold for mitotic entry was found to be between 32 and 40 nM cyclin B in the frog extracts while the inactivation threshold for exiting mitosis was lower, between 16 and 24 nM cyclin B.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The higher threshold for mitotic entry compared to the lower threshold for mitotic exit indicates hysteresis, a hallmark of history-dependent behavior in the system.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Concentrations between 24 and 32 nM cyclin B demonstrated bistability, where the system could exist in either interphase or mitosis, depending on its prior state (history).
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Though, the cell cycle is not completely irreversible, the difference in thresholds is enough for growth and survival of the cells.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteric thresholds in biological systems are not definite and can be recalibrated.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] For example, unreplicated DNA or chromosomes inhibits Cdc25 phosphatase and maintains Wee1 kinase activity.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This prevents the activation of Cyclin B-Cdc2, effectively raising the threshold for mitotic entry.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] As a result, the cell delays the transition to mitosis until replication is complete, ensuring genomic integrity.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Other instances may be DNA damage and unattached chromosomes during the spindle assembly checkpoint.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Biochemical systems can also show hysteresis-like output when slowly varying states that are not directly monitored are involved, as in the case of the cell cycle arrest in yeast exposed to mating pheromone.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The proposed model is that α-factor, a yeast mating pheromone binds to its analog receptor on another yeast cell promoting transcription of Fus3 and promoting mating.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Fus3 further promotes Far1 which inhibits Cln1/2, activators of the cell cycle.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This is representative of a coherent feedforward loop that can modeled as a hysteresis curve.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Far1 transcription is the primary mechanism responsible for the hysteresis observed in cell-cycle reentry.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The history of pheromone exposure influences the accumulation of Far1, which, in turn, determines the delay in cell-cycle reentry.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Previous pulse experiments demonstrated that after exposure to high pheromone concentrations, cells enter a stabilized arrested state where reentry thresholds are elevated due to increased Far1-dependent inhibition of CDK activity.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Even when pheromone levels drop to concentrations that would allow naive cells to reenter the cell cycle, pre-exposed cells take longer to resume proliferation.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This delay reflects the history-dependent nature of hysteresis, where past exposure to high pheromone concentrations influences the current state.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteresis ensures that cells make robust and irreversible decisions about mating and proliferation in response to pheromone signals.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] It allows cells to "remember" high pheromone exposure, and this helps yeast cells adapt and stability their responses to environmental conditions, avoiding fast premature reentry into the cell cycle, the moment that pheromone signal dies down.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Additionally, the duration of cell cycle arrest depends not only on the final level of input Fus3, but also on the previously achieved Fus3 levels.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Experiments in this type of hysteresis benefit from the ability to change the concentration of the inputs with time.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The mechanisms are often elucidated by allowing independent control of the concentration of the key intermediate, for instance, by using an inducible promoter.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Here, the duration of cell cycle arrest depends not only on the final level of input Fus3, but also on the previously achieved Fus3 levels.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In developmental biology, cell type diversity is regulated by long range-acting signaling molecules called morphogens that pattern uniform pools of cells in a concentration- and time-dependent manner.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The morphogen sonic hedgehog (Shh), for example, acts on limb bud and neural progenitors to induce expression of a set of homeodomain-containing transcription factors to subdivide these tissues into distinct domains.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] It has been shown that these tissues have a 'memory' of previous exposure to Shh.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In neural tissue, this hysteresis is regulated by a homeodomain (HD) feedback circuit that amplifies Shh signaling.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In this circuit, expression of Gli transcription factors, the executors of the Shh pathway, is suppressed.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Glis are processed to repressor forms (GliR) in the absence of Shh, but in the presence of Shh, a proportion of Glis are maintained as full-length proteins allowed to translocate to the nucleus, where they act as activators (GliA) of transcription.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] By reducing Gli expression then, the HD transcription factors reduce the total amount of Gli (GliT), so a higher proportion of GliT can be stabilized as GliA for the same concentration of Shh.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] There is some evidence that T cells exhibit hysteresis in that it takes a lower signal threshold to activate T cells that have been previously activated.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Ras GTPase activation is required for downstream effector functions of activated T cells.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Triggering of the T cell receptor induces high levels of Ras activation, which results in higher levels of GTP-bound (active) Ras at the cell surface.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The property by which some neurons do not return to their basal conditions from a stimulated condition immediately after removal of the stimulus is an example of hysteresis.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Neuropsychology, in exploring the neural correlates of consciousness, interfaces with neuroscience, although the complexity of the central nervous system is a challenge to its study (that is, its operation resists easy reduction).
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Context-dependent memory and state-dependent memory show hysteretic aspects of neurocognition.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Lung hysteresis is evident when observing the compliance of a lung on inspiration versus expiration.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The difference in compliance (Δvolume/Δpressure) is due to the additional energy required to overcome surface tension forces during inspiration to recruit and inflate additional alveoli.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The transpulmonary pressure vs Volume curve of inhalation is different from the Pressure vs Volume curve of exhalation, the difference being described as hysteresis.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Lung volume at any given pressure during inhalation is less than the lung volume at any given pressure during exhalation.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] A hysteresis effect may be observed in voicing onset versus offset.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The threshold value of the subglottal pressure required to start the vocal fold vibration is lower than the threshold value at which the vibration stops, when other parameters are kept constant.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In utterances of vowel-voiceless consonant-vowel sequences during speech, the intraoral pressure is lower at the voice onset of the second vowel compared to the voice offset of the first vowel, the oral airflow is lower, the transglottal pressure is larger and the glottal width is smaller.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteresis is a commonly encountered phenomenon in ecology and epidemiology, where the observed equilibrium of a system can not be predicted solely based on environmental variables, but also requires knowledge of the system's past history.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Notable examples include the theory of spruce budworm outbreaks and behavioral-effects on disease transmission.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] It is commonly examined in relation to critical transitions between ecosystem or community types in which dominant competitors or entire landscapes can change in a largely irreversible fashion.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Complex ocean and climate models rely on the principle.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Economic systems can exhibit hysteresis.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] For example, export performance is subject to strong hysteresis effects: because of the fixed transportation costs it may take a big push to start a country's exports, but once the transition is made, not much may be required to keep them going.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] When some negative shock reduces employment in a company or industry, fewer employed workers then remain.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] As usually the employed workers have the power to set wages, their reduced number incentivizes them to bargain for higher wages when the economy again gets better instead of letting the wage be at the equilibrium wage level, where the supply and demand of workers would match.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This causes hysteresis: the unemployment becomes permanently higher after negative shocks.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The idea of hysteresis is used extensively in the area of labor economics, specifically with reference to the unemployment rate.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In addition, employers may use time spent in unemployment as a screening tool, i.e., to weed out less desired employees in hiring decisions.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Then, in times of an economic upturn, recovery, or "boom", the affected workers will not share in the prosperity, remaining unemployed for long periods (e.g., over 52 weeks).
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] This makes unemployment "structural", i.e., extremely difficult to reduce simply by increasing the aggregate demand for products and labor without causing increased inflation.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] That is, it is possible that a ratchet effect in unemployment rates exists, so a short-term rise in unemployment rates tends to persist.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] For example, traditional anti-inflationary policy (the use of recession to fight inflation) leads to a permanently higher "natural" rate of unemployment (more scientifically known as the NAIRU).
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The existence of hysteresis has been put forward as a possible explanation for the persistently high unemployment of many economies in the 1990s.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteresis has been invoked by Olivier Blanchard among others to explain the differences in long run unemployment rates between Europe and the United States.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Labor market reform (usually meaning institutional change promoting more flexible wages, firing, and hiring) or strong demand-side economic growth may not therefore reduce this pool of long-term unemployed.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Thus, specific targeted training programs are presented as a possible policy solution.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] However, the hysteresis hypothesis suggests such training programs are aided by persistently high demand for products (perhaps with incomes policies to avoid increased inflation), which reduces the transition costs out of unemployment and into paid employment easier.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteretic models are mathematical models capable of simulating complex nonlinear behavior (hysteresis) characterizing mechanical systems and materials used in different fields of engineering, such as aerospace, civil, and mechanical engineering.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Each subject that involves hysteresis has models that are specific to the subject.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In addition, there are hysteretic models that capture general features of many systems with hysteresis.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] An example is the Preisach model of hysteresis, which represents a hysteresis nonlinearity as a linear superposition of square loops called non-ideal relays.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Many complex models of hysteresis arise from the simple parallel connection, or superposition, of elementary carriers of hysteresis termed hysterons.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] A simple and intuitive parametric description of various hysteresis loops may be found in the Lapshin model.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Along with the smooth loops, substitution of trapezoidal, triangular or rectangular pulses instead of the harmonic functions allows piecewise-linear hysteresis loops frequently used in discrete automatics to be built in the model.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] There are implementations of the hysteresis loop model in Mathcad and in R programming language.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The Bouc–Wen model of hysteresis is often used to describe non-linear hysteretic systems.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] It was introduced by Bouc and extended by Wen, who demonstrated its versatility by producing a variety of hysteretic patterns.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The most important extension of Bouc-Wen Model was carried out by Baber and Noori and later by Noori and co-workers.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] That extended model, named, BWBN, can reproduce the complex shear pinching or slip-lock phenomenon that earlier model could not reproduce.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] The BWBN model has been widely used in a wide spectrum of applications and implementations are available in software such as OpenSees.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Hysteretic models may have a generalized displacement u as input variable and a generalized force f as output variable, or vice versa.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] In particular, in rate-independent hysteretic models, the output variable does not depend on the rate of variation of the input one.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] Some notable hysteretic models are listed below, along with their associated fields.
[src:magnetic-materials/hysteresis] When hysteresis occurs with extensive and intensive variables, the work done on the system is the area under the hysteresis graph.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] A **magnetic domain** is a region within a magnetic material in which the magnetization is in a uniform direction.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] This means that the individual magnetic moments of the atoms are aligned with one another and they point in the same direction.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] When cooled below a temperature called the Curie temperature, the magnetization of a piece of ferromagnetic material spontaneously divides into many small regions called magnetic domains.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The magnetization within each domain points in a uniform direction, but the magnetization of different domains may point in different directions.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Magnetic domain structure is responsible for the magnetic behavior of ferromagnetic materials like aluminium, iron, cobalt, nickel, copper, silver, gold and their alloys, and ferrimagnetic materials like ferrite.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] This includes the formation of permanent magnets and the attraction of ferromagnetic materials to a magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The regions separating magnetic domains are called domain walls, where the magnetization rotates coherently from the direction in one domain to that in the next domain.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The study of magnetic domains is called micromagnetics.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Magnetic domains form in materials which have magnetic ordering; that is, their dipoles spontaneously align due to the exchange interaction.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] These are the ferromagnetic, ferrimagnetic and antiferromagnetic materials.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Paramagnetic and diamagnetic materials, in which the dipoles align in response to an external field but do not spontaneously align, do not have magnetic domains.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Magnetic domain theory was developed by French physicist Pierre-Ernest Weiss who, in 1906, suggested existence of magnetic domains in ferromagnets.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] He suggested that large number of atomic magnetic moments (typically 1012-1018) were aligned parallel.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The direction of alignment varies from domain to domain in a more or less random manner, although certain crystallographic axis may be preferred by the magnetic moments, called easy axes.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Weiss still had to explain the reason for the spontaneous alignment of atomic moments within a ferromagnetic material, and he came up with the so-called Weiss mean field.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] He assumed that a given magnetic moment in a material experienced a very high effective magnetic field **He** due to the magnetization of its neighbors.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] In the original Weiss theory the mean field was proportional to the bulk magnetization **M**, so that $H_{e}=\alpha M$ where $\alpha$ is the mean field constant.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] However this is not applicable to ferromagnets due to the variation of magnetization from domain to domain.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] where $M_{s}$ is the saturation magnetization at 0K.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Later, the quantum theory made it possible to understand the microscopic origin of the Weiss field.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The reason a piece of magnetic material such as iron spontaneously divides into separate domains, rather than exist in a state with magnetization in the same direction throughout the material, is to minimize its internal energy.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] A large region of ferromagnetic material with a constant magnetization throughout will create a large magnetic field extending into the space outside itself *(diagram a)*.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] This requires a lot of *magnetostatic energy* stored in the field.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] To reduce this energy, the sample can split into two domains, with the magnetization in opposite directions in each domain *(diagram b)*.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The magnetic field lines pass in loops in opposite directions through each domain, reducing the field outside the material.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] To reduce the field energy further, each of these domains can split also, resulting in smaller parallel domains with magnetization in alternating directions, with smaller amounts of field outside the material.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The domain structure of actual magnetic materials does not usually form by the process of large domains splitting into smaller ones as described here.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] When a sample is cooled below the Curie temperature, for example, the equilibrium domain configuration simply appears.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] But domains can split, and the description of domains splitting is often used to reveal the energy tradeoffs in domain formation.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] As explained above a domain which is too big is unstable, and will divide into smaller domains.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] But a small enough domain will be stable and will not split, and this determines the size of the domains created in a material.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] This size depends on the balance of several energies within the material.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Each time a region of magnetization splits into two domains, it creates a domain wall between the domains, where magnetic dipoles (molecules) with magnetization pointing in different directions are adjacent.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The exchange interaction which creates the magnetization is a force which tends to align nearby dipoles so they point in the same direction.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Forcing adjacent dipoles to point in different directions requires energy.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Therefore, a domain wall requires extra energy, called the domain wall energy, which is proportional to the area of the wall.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Thus the net amount that the energy is reduced when a domain splits is equal to the difference between the magnetic field energy saved, and the additional energy required to create the domain wall.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The field energy is proportional to the cube of the domain size, while the domain wall energy is proportional to the square of the domain size.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] So as the domains get smaller, the net energy saved by splitting decreases.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The domains keep dividing into smaller domains until the energy cost of creating an additional domain wall is just equal to the field energy saved.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Then the domains of this size are stable.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] In most materials the domains are microscopic in size, around 10−4 - 10−6 m.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] An additional way for the material to further reduce its magnetostatic energy is to form domains with magnetization at right angles to the other domains *(diagram c)*, instead of just in opposing parallel directions.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] These domains, called *flux closure domains*, allow the field lines to turn 180° within the material, forming closed loops entirely within the material, reducing the magnetostatic energy to zero.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] However, forming these domains incurs two additional energy costs.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] First, the crystal lattice of most magnetic materials has magnetic anisotropy, which means it has an "easy" direction of magnetization, parallel to one of the crystal axes.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Changing the magnetization of the material to any other direction takes additional energy, called the "*magnetocrystalline anisotropy energy*".
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The other energy cost to creating domains with magnetization at an angle to the "easy" direction is caused by the phenomenon called magnetostriction.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] When the magnetization of a piece of magnetic material is changed to a different direction, it causes a slight change in its shape.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The change in magnetic field causes the magnetic dipole molecules to change shape slightly, making the crystal lattice longer in one dimension and shorter in other dimensions.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] However, since the magnetic domain is "squished in" with its boundaries held rigid by the surrounding material, it cannot actually change shape.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] So instead, changing the direction of the magnetization induces tiny mechanical stresses in the material, requiring more energy to create the domain.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] This is called "*magnetoelastic anisotropy energy*".
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] To form these closure domains with "sideways" magnetization requires additional energy due to the aforementioned two factors.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] So flux closure domains will only form where the magnetostatic energy saved is greater than the sum of the "exchange energy" to create the domain wall, the magnetocrystalline anisotropy energy, and the magnetoelastic anisotropy energy.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The above describes magnetic domain structure in a perfect crystal lattice, such as would be found in a single crystal of iron.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] However most magnetic materials are polycrystalline, composed of microscopic crystalline grains.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] These grains are *not* the same as domains.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Each grain is a little crystal, with the crystal lattices of separate grains oriented in random directions.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] In most materials, each grain is big enough to contain several domains.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Each crystal has an "easy" axis of magnetization, and is divided into domains with the axis of magnetization parallel to this axis, in alternate directions.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] In its lowest energy state, the magnetization of neighboring domains point in different directions, confining the field lines to microscopic loops between neighboring domains within the material, so the combined fields cancel at a distance.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Therefore, a bulk piece of ferromagnetic material in its lowest energy state has little or no external magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The material is said to be "unmagnetized".
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] However, the domains can also exist in other configurations in which their magnetization mostly points in the same direction, creating an external magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Although these are not minimum energy configurations, due to a phenomenon where the domain walls become "pinned" to defects in the crystal lattice they can be *local* minimums of the energy, and therefore can be very stable.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Applying an external magnetic field to the material can make the domain walls move, causing the domains aligned with the field to grow, and the opposing domains to shrink.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] When the external field is removed, the domain walls remain pinned in their new orientation and the aligned domains produce a magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] This is what happens when a piece of ferromagnetic material is "magnetized" and becomes a permanent magnet.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The contributions of the different internal energy factors described above is expressed by the free energy equation proposed by Lev Landau and Evgeny Lifshitz in 1935, which forms the basis of the modern theory of magnetic domains.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The domain structure of a material is the one which minimizes the Gibbs free energy of the material.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Some sources define a wall energy *EW* equal to the sum of the exchange energy and the magnetocrystalline anisotropy energy, which replaces *Eex* and *Ek* in the above equation.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] A stable domain structure is a magnetization function ***M***(***x***), considered as a continuous vector field, which minimizes the total energy *E* throughout the material.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] To find the minimums a variational method is used, resulting in a set of nonlinear differential equations, called *Brown's equations* after William Fuller Brown Jr.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Although in principle these equations can be solved for the stable domain configurations ***M***(***x***), in practice only the simplest examples can be solved.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Analytic solutions do not exist, and numerical solutions calculated by the finite element method are computationally intractable because of the large difference in scale between the domain size and the wall size.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Therefore, micromagnetics has evolved approximate methods which assume that the magnetization of dipoles in the bulk of the domain, away from the wall, all point in the same direction, and numerical solutions are only used near the domain wall, where the magnetization is changing rapidly.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] There are a number of microscopy methods that can be used to visualize the magnetization at the surface of a magnetic material, revealing the magnetic domains.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Each method has a different application because not all domains are the same.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] In magnetic materials, domains can be circular, square, irregular, elongated, and striped, all of which have varied sizes and dimensions.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Large domains, within the range of 25-100 micrometers can be easily seen by Kerr microscopy, which uses the magneto-optic Kerr effect, which is the rotation of the polarization of light reflected from a magnetized surface.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Lorentz microscopy is a collection of transmission electron microscopy techniques used to study magnetic domain structures down to the nanoscale.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Most common techniques include Fresnel mode, Foucault mode and low-angle electron diffraction (LAD) in parallel beam TEM mode, and differential phase contrast (DPC) in scanning TEM mode.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Off-axis electron holography is a related technique used to observe magnetic structures by detecting nanoscale magnetic fields.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Another technique for viewing sub-microscopic domain structures down to a scale of a few nanometers is magnetic force microscopy.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] MFM is a form of atomic force microscopy that uses a magnetically coated probe tip to scan the sample surface.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] Bitter patterns are a technique for imaging magnetic domains that were first observed by Francis Bitter.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The technique involves placing a small quantity of ferrofluid on the surface of a ferromagnetic material.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] The ferrofluid arranges itself along magnetic domain walls, which have higher magnetic flux than the regions of the material located within domains.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetic-domain] A modified Bitter technique has been incorporated into a widely used device, the Large Area Domain Viewer, which is particularly useful in the examination of grain-oriented silicon steels.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] The familiar effects occur in ferromagnetic materials, which are strongly attracted by magnetic fields and can be magnetized to become permanent magnets, producing magnetic fields themselves.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] Demagnetizing a magnet is also possible.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] Only a few substances are ferromagnetic; the most common ones are iron, cobalt, nickel, and their alloys.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] All substances exhibit some type of magnetism.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] Magnetic materials are classified according to their bulk susceptibility.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] Ferromagnetism is responsible for most of the effects of magnetism encountered in everyday life, but there are actually several types of magnetism.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] Paramagnetic substances, such as aluminium and oxygen, are weakly attracted to an applied magnetic field; diamagnetic substances, such as copper and carbon, are weakly repelled; while antiferromagnetic materials, such as chromium, have a more complex relationship with a magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] The force of a magnet on paramagnetic, diamagnetic, and antiferromagnetic materials is usually too weak to be felt and can be detected only by laboratory instruments, so in everyday life, these substances are often described as non-magnetic.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] The strength of a magnetic field always decreases with distance from the magnetic source, though the exact mathematical relationship between strength and distance varies.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] Many factors can influence the magnetic field of an object including the magnetic moment of the material, the physical shape of the object, both the magnitude and direction of any electric current present within the object, and the temperature of the object.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] Magnetism was first discovered in the ancient world when people noticed that lodestones, naturally magnetized pieces of the mineral magnetite, could attract iron.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] The word *magnet* comes from the Greek term μαγνῆτις λίθος *magnētis lithos*, "the Magnesian stone, lodestone".
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] In ancient Greece, Aristotle attributed the first of what could be called a scientific discussion of magnetism to the philosopher Thales of Miletus, who lived from about 625 BCE to about 545 BCE.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] The ancient Indian medical text *Sushruta Samhita* describes using magnetite to remove arrows embedded in a person's body.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] In ancient China, the earliest literary reference to magnetism lies in a 4th-century BCE book named after its author, *Guiguzi*.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] By the 12th century, the Chinese were known to use the lodestone compass for navigation.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] They sculpted a directional spoon from lodestone in such a way that the handle of the spoon always pointed south.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] Alexander Neckam, by 1187, was the first in Europe to describe the compass and its use for navigation.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] In 1269, Peter Peregrinus de Maricourt wrote the *Epistola de magnete*, the first extant treatise describing the properties of magnets.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] In 1282, the properties of magnets and the dry compasses were discussed by Al-Ashraf Umar II, a Yemeni physicist, astronomer, and geographer.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] Leonardo Garzoni's only extant work, the *Due trattati sopra la natura, e le qualità della calamita* (*Two treatises on the nature and qualities of the magnet*), is the first known example of a modern treatment of magnetic phenomena.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] Written in years near 1580 and never published, the treatise had a wide diffusion.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] In particular, Garzoni is referred to as an expert in magnetism by Niccolò Cabeo, whose Philosophia Magnetica (1629) is just a re-adjustment of Garzoni's work.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] Garzoni's treatise was known also to Giovanni Battista Della Porta.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] In 1600, William Gilbert published his *De Magnete, Magneticisque Corporibus, et de Magno Magnete Tellure* (*On the Magnet and Magnetic Bodies, and on the Great Magnet the Earth*).
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] In this work he describes many of his experiments with his model earth called the terrella.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] From his experiments, he concluded that the Earth was itself magnetic and that this was the reason compasses pointed north whereas, previously, some believed that it was the pole star Polaris or a large magnetic island on the north pole that attracted the compass.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] An understanding of the relationship between electricity and magnetism began in 1819 with work by Hans Christian Ørsted, a professor at the University of Copenhagen, who discovered, by the accidental twitching of a compass needle near a wire, that an electric current could create a magnetic field.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] This landmark experiment is known as Ørsted's Experiment.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] Jean-Baptiste Biot and Félix Savart, both of whom in 1820 came up with the Biot–Savart law giving an equation for the magnetic field from a current-carrying wire.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] In 1831, Michael Faraday discovered that a time-varying magnetic flux induces a voltage through a wire loop.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] In 1835, Carl Friedrich Gauss hypothesized, based on Ampère's force law in its original form, that all forms of magnetism arise as a result of elementary point charges moving relative to each other.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] Wilhelm Eduard Weber advanced Gauss's theory to Weber electrodynamics.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] From around 1861, James Clerk Maxwell synthesized and expanded many of these insights into Maxwell's equations, unifying electricity, magnetism, and optics into the field of electromagnetism.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] However, Gauss's interpretation of magnetism is not fully compatible with Maxwell's electrodynamics.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] In 1905, Albert Einstein used Maxwell's equations in motivating his theory of special relativity, requiring that the laws hold true in all inertial reference frames.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] Gauss's approach of interpreting the magnetic force as a mere effect of relative velocities thus found its way back into electrodynamics to some extent.
[src:magnetic-materials/magnetism] Electromagnetism has continued to develop into the 21st century, being incorporated into the more fundamental theories of gauge theory, quantum electrodynamics, electroweak theory, and finally the Standard Model.
